Reduction of aldehyde emission and attribution of environment burden in

cooking fumes from food stalls using a novel fume collector

A B S T R A C T

Uncontrolled cooking emissions from commercial kitchens are problematic due to their corresponding health

effects and malodors. To reduce cooking emissions, medium and large commercial kitchens install air pollution

control devices, such as electrostatic precipitators and wet scrubbers, while small-scale commercial cooking

workplaces, such as street-food stalls, use smaller, simpler, and less costly filtration and absorption devices.

However, these smaller devices may be poorly designed and recirculate cooking emissions in the workplace. The

objectives of this study were to design and implement a novel fume collector and evaluate its effectiveness in

reducing aldehydes and the corresponding environmental burden emitted by food stalls. Two stalls, which had

malodor problems despite the use of fume collectors, volunteered to participate in the study. To increase the

efficiency of the existing fume collectors, a new collector was designed comprising two buckets connected in

series, each with pollutant absorption (NaClO-surfactant mixed solution) and particulate filtration (activated-

carbon filters) components. Total aldehyde concentrations measured at the exhaust outlets of the original and

new collectors were 342.2 and 80.8 μg/m3 for stall A, and 622.7 and 283.1 μg/m3 for stall B, respectively. The

corresponding concentration reductions for stall A and B were 76% and 55%, and the emission rate reductions

were 91% (from 749 to 71 g/yr) and 76% (from 1040 g/yr to 248 g/h), respectively. These results demonstrate

that the effectiveness of the novel collector at removing cooking fumes was significantly improved. The high

efficiency and low-cost nature of the collector make it highly applicable in small-scale commercial kitchens and

street-food stalls.

1. Introduction

Cooking oil fumes (COFs) from commercial kitchens raise public

concern as considerable amounts of pollutants are emitted, some of

which are associated with adverse health effects or are considered a

nuisance. Epidemiological studies indicate that exposure to COFs is

linked to respiratory diseases and impaired lung function (Neghab et al.,

2017; Chen et al., 2018). Notably, meta-analysis studies have linked

COFs to lung cancer in nonsmoking Chinese women (Lee and Gany

2013; Xue et al., 2016). A nationwide database analysis in Taiwan also

revealed higher risks of lung cancer and other cancers for Chinese food

chefs than for non-Chinese food chefs, particularly in females (Lin et al.,

2019). Furthermore, the International Agency of Research on Cancer has

categorized emissions from high-temperature frying as a probable

carcinogen (Group 2 A) (IARC 2012).

The significant adverse human health effects of cooking emissions

are related to their chemical composition. Harmful chemicals identified

in cooking fumes include polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, aldehydes,

volatile organic compounds, and fine particulates (Wang et al., 2017;

Zhao and Zhao 2018; Sharma and Balasubramanian 2020). Of these

pollutants, benzo(a)pyrene, formaldehyde, and acetaldehyde are clas­

sified as known or probable carcinogens. Another pollutant, t,t-2,

4-decadienal (t,t-2,4-DDE), increases intracellular peroxide, damages

DNA, and releases pro-inflammatory cytokines related to genotoxicity

and tumor promotion (Chang et al., 2005). Aldehydes, which are among

the most abundant species in cooking fumes, are produced by fatty acid

degradation, and their emissions vary with cooking temperature and oil

composition (Katragadda et al., 2010; Zhang et al., 2019). In addition to

having adverse health effects, several long-chain aldehydes are associ­

ated with malodor. For example, t,t-2,4-DDE and nonanal have a fatty,

rancid, and tallow smell (Garcia-Gonzalez et al., 2013). Thus, aldehydes

can be considered a characteristic species of COFs in terms of their

health effects, abundance, and odor.

Reducing cooking emissions is essential for minimizing personal

exposure, corresponding health effects, and environmental impacts. An

exposure study revealed a significantly higher cancer risk in street food

cart workers compared to workers in western fast food restaurant

kitchens (p < 0.001) and in Chinese cafeteria kitchens (p = 0.013),

probably due to a lack of effective fume extraction systems for street

food carts (Wu et al., 2019). A novel ventilation system designed by Liu

et al. (2020) provided an upward air curtain around a gas stove, thereby

conditioning air near the cook. This system, which included a hood to

control exhaust fumes, had a high particle capture efficiency

(96.2–97.1%) and the proportion of cooks dissatisfied with the venti­

lation system was lower than 20%. The exhaust system consists of a

hood, ducting, air-cleaning device, fan, and an exhaust outlet (Canadian

Centre for Occupational Health and Safety, 2016). Several studies pro­

vide suggestions for the exhaust air-flow rate, hood shape, and attach­

ment installation (i.e., side panel, front overhang, etc.) to increase the

capture efficiency of pollutants and to draw pollutants away from the

breathing zone of the cooks (Zhao et al., 2019; Zhao and Zhao 2020).

One report evaluated different air-cleaning devices and showed that the

efficiencies of mechanical filters, electrostatic precipitators (ESPs), wet

scrubbers, and ultra-violet (UV)/ozone devices (UV/O3) at removing

cooking fumes were in the range of 20–40%, 70–90%, 60–80%, and

80–90%, respectively (Taipei Government 2018). Emerging technolo­

gies for treating COFs include catalytic incinerators (Ho et al., 2019),

photocatalytic reactors and ozone oxidation (Li et al., 2018), biofilters

(Yan et al., 2021), and rotating packed beds (Li et al., 2018; Lin et al.,

2020). Under optimal conditions, these technologies can achieve >80%

removal efficiencies.

Medium and large commercial kitchens are legally required to install

air pollution control devices and must comply with emission standards.

Air pollution prevention regulations in China and Taiwan (Standing

Committee of the National People’s Congress, 2018, Taiwan Environ­

mental Protection Administration, 2018) prohibit the uncontrolled

emission of cooking fumes from commercial kitchens into the atmo­

sphere. However, drawbacks of air-cleaning devices with high removal

efficiencies include their high energy consumption (e.g., ESPs, catalytic

incinerators, and photocatalytic reactors), large capital investment re­

quirements, and/or costly maintenance (e.g., ESPs, wet scrubber, and

UV/O3 devices), and the need for trained personnel for their operation

and maintenance (e.g., biofilters and rotating packed beds).

These devices are not well suited to street food stalls or small com­

mercial kitchens, which are exempt from these regulations because of

their relatively small scale (generally with capital investments < NT

$100,000 and a workplace area of <100 m2). However, according to the

Statistical Bureau of Taiwan, the number of street food stalls had

reached approximately 164,000 in 2018 (Directorate General of Budget

Accounting and Statistics, 2018). Street food stalls generate consider­

able emissions not only in Taiwan but in many countries throughout the

world (Chan et al., 2016; Wu et al., 2019; Hsu et al., 2020; Nahar et al.,

2020). These emissions affect the surrounding environment, posing

health concerns of those people exposed to them.

The typical street food stall is a small owner-operated business

established at a single location and run by one or two workers. The

owners of these small enterprises can rarely afford costly air-cleaning

devices and rarely have even rudimentary knowledge of the operation

and maintenance of complex air-cleaning devices. For such small com­

mercial kitchens and food stalls, air-cleaning devices must be simple and

economical. Hydrocarbons can be efficiently removed by using sodium

hypochlorite (NaClO) in a chemical scrubber (Cheng and Hsieh 2010) or

by using NaClO and surfactant in a co-current rotating packed bed (Li

et al., 2018). In an aqueous solution, NaClO forms HClO, which is a

strong oxidant that produces free radicals that react with the hydro­

carbons in COFs (Cheng and Hsieh 2010). Adding surfactants substan­

tially increases the solubility of hydrophobic compounds in these

aqueous solutions (Neogi and Munden 2007). Both NaClO and surfac­

tants are easily obtained; however, none of the common devices (i.e.,

wet scrubbers and rotating packed beds) are feasible for use in small

commercial kitchens due to budget and space constraints. Therefore, for

small commercial kitchens, development is needed to design systems

able to bring cooking emissions into contact with NaClO-surfactant

mixed solutions.

Here, an impinger device able to chemically and physically extract

pollutants from air bubbled through a liquid was applied (Nishikawa

and Sakai 1995; SKC Inc, 2018). Specifically, the cooking exhaust

captured by the fume extractor was dissolved as it came in contact with a

sodium hypochlorite/neutral detergent solution contained in a series of

two well-sealed buckets. In doing so, this is the first study to apply the

impinger concept to the use of a NaClO-surfactant solution to control

cooking exhaust pollution. The specific objectives of the study were to

(1) evaluate a novel design for a device that collects COFs and dissolves

them through contact with a NaClO-surfactant solution, and (2) evaluate

the effectiveness of the device in reducing aldehyde, a characteristic

COF pollutant species.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Food stall selection and sampling strategy

The owners of two food stalls with malodor problems (stall A:

22◦38′37.3′′N,

120◦18′23.2′′E;

and

stall

B:

22◦38′37.9′′N,

120◦17′54.5′′E) volunteered to participate in the study and agreed to

install the proposed fume collectors to control cooking emissions. The

cooking method primarily used in both food stalls was deep-frying,

which generates considerable amounts of COFs (Zhao and Zhao 2018;

Sharma and Balasubramanian 2020). Both stalls were located on ve­

randas facing the street, with work areas of 22.5 m2 (4.5 m × 5 m) and

18 m2 (4 m × 4.5 m), respectively. The main cooking ingredients used by

the food stalls were meats (e.g., chicken and pork) followed by root and

stem vegetables (e.g., potato, sweet yam, and bean). The oil used for

cooking was palm oil on stall A and a palm-soybean blended oil on stall

B. Both stalls used liquefied petroleum gas as the cooking fuel (Table 1).

The components of the existing cooking fume extraction system on

stall A were an enclosure hood with a 0.04–0.34 m/s capture velocity

(measured at the opening of the hood, Supplementary Fig. S1), a 1-hp

(0.735-kW) motor, and a 25-cm duct (9–10 m/s duct velocity). The

extraction system for stall B included an exterior hood with a 0.26–0.35

m/s capture velocity (Supplementary Fig. S1), a 0.5-hp (0.368 kW)

motor, and a 15-cm duct (10–11 m/s duct velocity). Air velocity was

measured using an anemometer (Testo 425). The fume extraction system

captured cooking fumes and routed the captured air into the fume col­

lector for treatment, after which the treated fumes were released into the

atmosphere through the duct. As both stalls were located on verandas

rather than inside buildings, the component air was derived from the

surrounding outdoor area. Table 1 shows the specifications and char­

acteristics of the two food stalls.

Area samples were taken during the opening hours for stall A and

stall B (9 h and 10 h, respectively). In each sampling campaign, samples

T.-C. Wu et al.

Environmental Research 195 (2021) 110815

3

were collected at the following six sites: (1) the exhaust outlet of the

fume collector, (2) the wok edge, (3) the cook working area, (4) the

food-preparation area, (5) the ordering counter, and (6) in the street

(Fig. 1). With the exception of samples collected at the wok edge and the

exhaust outlet, all samples were collected at a height of 1.5 m, which is

the breathing zone for a worker standing upright. Each food stall was

sampled during two campaigns, both before and after the intervention,

which involved replacing the existing fume collector with the new type

described here.

2.2. Novel fume collector

The original fume collector on stall A was filled with water/bleach

solution. The connecting tube from the fume hood to the collector was

not immersed into the bleach solution (loosely positioned around the lid

of the fume collector) and the lid was not fully sealed (Supplementary

Fig. S2). The existing collector on stall B was very similar to stall A,

except that it had multiple holes (Supplementary Fig. S3). Therefore,

these existing fume collectors did not capture cooking exhaust effi­

ciently as fumes could escape through the unsealed lid and the holes in

the collector before coming in contact with the bleaching solution.

The new fume collectors were impinger-type devices consisting of

two polypropylene buckets with screw-on lids, connection tubing,

activated carbon-impregnated polyester filters (activated carbon con­

tent ~40%, Hangzhou Shilan Filter Technology Co., China), sodium

hypochlorite solution (NaClO 12%, Kao Chemicals Co., Taiwan), and

neutral detergent (the active ingredient was sodium dodecyl benzene

sulfonate, PanReac AppliChem, Spain) (Fig. 2). The lid of each bucket

was tightly screw-on and sealed with silicone. The top of each bucket

had one large and one small hole acting to accommodate the passing gas

and a refill valve, respectively. Additionally, the sides of the buckets had

a large and small hole for the passing gas and a drain valve, respectively.

Activated carbon filters placed inside the connection tubing and the

exhaust outlet of the fume collector were used to remove gaseous pol­

lutants and additional particulates.

The new fume collectors were operated as follows. Cooking exhaust

from the fume hood passed through the sodium hypochlorite/neutral

detergent solution in the first bucket. After reaction with or dissolution

in the solution, the outflow gas from the first bucket passed through two

layers of activated carbon filters, reacted with the solution in the second

bucket, then passed through the filters and into the ambient air (Fig. 2).

This assembly comprised two impingers connected in series, allow for

improved collection efficiencies (>81%), (Nishikawa and Sakai 1995;

Montesinos et al., 2015).

The fume collectors used on the two food stalls were different sizes to

accommodate the available space on their respective verandas and the

cooking fume extraction system. Large buckets (capacity = 140 L,

diameter = 610 mm, height = 740 mm) were used for the collector on

stall A, with each containing 50 L of the sodium hypochlorite/neutral

detergent solution, with a 5-cm-diameter refill valve and a 5-cm-

diameter drain valve (Supplementary Fig. S2). Smaller buckets (capac­

ity = 35 L, diameter = 385 mm, height = 435 mm) were used for the

collector on stall B, each containing 20 L of the solution, with a 5-cm-

diameter refill valve and a 5-cm-diameter drain valve (Supplementary

Fig. S3). Supplementary Figs. S2 and S3 provide additional details of the

fume collectors. The concentrations of sodium hypochlorite (2352 ppm)

and neutral detergent (300 ppm) were the same for both fume collectors,

which were adopted from Cheng et al. (2008).

2.3. Sampling and analysis

As aldehydes are critical species in cooking fumes in terms of health

effects, abundance, and odor, aldehyde concentrations and emission

rates were used to evaluate the efficiency of the new fume collectors.

The 13 aldehydes targeted for analysis (Supplementary Table S1) have

well-known health hazards (e.g., formaldehyde and acetaldehyde) or are

known to occur in COFs (e.g., nonanal and t,t-2,4-DDE). The sampling

train used to collect aldehydes included an IOM sampler with a DNPH-

coated glass fiber filter (25 mm × 2 μm pore size, Supelco; Bellefonte,

Pennsylvania, USA) and a 2,4-DNPH cartridge (Supelco; Bellefonte,

Pennsylvania, USA) connected in series for particulate- and gaseous-

phase aldehyde sampling (Supplementary Fig. S4 (Peng et al., 2017)).

After sampling, the samples were stored at 4 ◦C in sealed aluminum bags

until extraction. Samples were extracted using acetonitrile and then

analyzed with a high-performance liquid chromatograph (PU-2089,

Jasco, Japan) equipped with an ultraviolet detector operated at 360 nm

(Varian ProStar 320, Varian, USA). A reverse-phase column (Ascentis®

RP-Amide Column, 5 μm, 250 × 4.6 mm, Supelco, Bellefonte, Pennsyl­

vania, USA) with a gradient mobile phase of acetonitrile/water was used

to separate the aldehydes. The gradient program was performed at a 1.2

ml/min flow rate as follows: an acetonitrile/water ratio of 40/60 for 1

min; an increase in acetonitrile from 40% to 90% within 49 min; held for

3 min; and a decrease in acetonitrile from 90% to 40% within 12 min.

Analytical quality controls for the 13 aldehydes yielded a filter re­

covery rate of 48.0–99.0%, a cartridge recovery rate of 46.1–95.7%,

reproducibility (coefficient of variation) of 0.9–3.6%, linearity (r2 of the

regression line) of 0.9984–0.9997, a filter method detection limit of

0.078–0.380 μg/m3, and a cartridge method detection limit of

0.113–0.786 μg/m3 (Supplementary Table S1).

2.4. Data analysis

Wilcoxon signed-rank tests were used to compare the pollutant

concentrations before and after installation of the new fume collector,

with all other conditions, such as cooking method, cooking food, and oil,

held constant. All statistical analyses were performed with IBM SPSS

Statistics 22 software (IBM SPSS Inc., Armonk, NY, USA). Statistically

significant differences were identified using a p-value (two-tailed) of

<0.05. Percentage differences (%Diff) was calculated as follows:

%Diff = (Cai −Cbi) / Cbi × 100%

3. Results and discussion

3.1. Aldehyde concentrations

Table 2 shows the aldehyde concentrations for stall A before and

after the intervention. Total aldehyde concentrations measured at the

outlet of the fume collector, wok edge, cook working site, ordering

counter, food preparation area, and street site were 342.2 μg/m3, 186.4

μg/m3, 239.0 μg/m3, 171.5 μg/m3, 121.9 μg/m3, and 54.6 μg/m3,

respectively, before the intervention; the respective concentrations after

the intervention were 80.8 μg/m3, 94.2 μg/m3, 163.1 μg/m3, 182.3 μg/

m3, 105.2 μg/m3, and 46.0 μg/m3. The largest reductions were observed

in the concentrations measured near the cooking source (76%, 49%, and

32% reductions at the fume collector outlet, wok edge, and cook

working area, respectively). Sites farther away from the cooking source,

e.g., the order counter and food preparation zone, did not show sub­

stantial reductions. Indeed, total aldehyde concentrations measured

near the order counter after intervention exceeded those measured

before installation. As discussed at the end of this section, this largely

reflects increases in the concentrations of acetaldehyde after the

installation. The percentage reduction at the street site was 16%

(Table 2). For the individual aldehydes, concentrations of formaldehyde,

propinoaldehyde, crotonaldehyde, hexaldehyde, t,t −2,4-nonadienal, t,

t-2,4-DDE, and nonanal were significantly lower after installation of the

new collector (Table 2, Fig. 3). Table S2 (see Supplementary Informa­

tion) shows that the respective percentage reductions for these aldehyde

types at sites near the cooking source were 49–78%, 70–96%, 67–90%,

84–93%, 4–97%, 56–66%, and 58–84%.

area, and street site, showed percentage reductions of 25%, 26%, and

considerably decreased. As both acetaldehyde and acrolein are volatile

compounds and predominantly occur in the gas-phase (Peng et al.,

2017), they disperse faster in comparison to particulate pollutants. For

both stalls, the fume extraction systems may not have provided suffi­

cient air-flow velocities for the hoods to capture gas-phase COFs. As a

result, quickly dispersed pollutants would not have been captured,

which may explain why short-chain aldehydes were not substantially

reduced by the intervention. Additional studies are now needed to un­

derstand the dispersive behavior of short-chain aldehydes to improve

the efficiency of their capture.

3.2. Emission rates

Aldehyde emission factors of particulate- and gas-phase aldehydes

were 0.04 and 0.29 g/h before, and 0.01 and 0.02 g/h after, the appli­

cation of the new fume collector on stall A. The equivalent values for

stall B were 0.05 and 0.36 g/h, and 0.03 and 0.07 g/h, respectively

(Table 4). These differences in emission factors were due to the change

in air velocity at the exhaust outlet of the fume collector. Specifically, air

velocity decreased from 5 to 6 m/s before the intervention to 2.2 m/s

after the intervention on stall A, and from 10 to 11 to 5–6 m/s on stall B

(Table 1). The corresponding emission rates for particulate, gaseous, and

total aldehydes were 99, 650, and 749 g/yr before the intervention

compared to 20, 51, and 71 g/yr afterward on stall A. As for stall B, the

corresponding emission rates were 132, 907, and 1040 g/yr before the

intervention and 83, 164, and 248 g/yr, afterward. These results indi­

cate total emission rate reductions of 678 and 792 g/yr for stalls A and B

alongside 91% and 76% reductions in aldehyde emissions, respectively.

Both stalls showed considerably reduced emissions after the imple­

mentation of the new fume collector; the reductions in emission factors

for stalls A and B were 0.3 and 0.32 g/h, respectively (Table 4). Thus,

0.3 g/h was the value used to estimate the potential reduction in

emissions that could be achieved in a scenario in which all food stalls in

Taiwan used the new fume collector (Table 5). Recent data indicate that

food stalls in Taiwan operate for an average of 1706 h annually (Envi­

ronmental Protection Administration of Taiwan, 2019). In 2018, the

number of street-food stalls operated in Taiwan reached 164,000

(Directorate General of Budget Accounting and Statistics, 2018). Thus, if

all food stalls applied the new fume collector system, annual aldehyde

emissions could be reduced by 84.29 tons/yr. Assuming that particulate-

and gaseous-phase emissions comprise an estimated 6–12% and 88–94%

of the total emissions, respectively (Table 5), reductions in these frac­

tions could be in the order of 5.24–9.78 and 74.51–79.05 tons/yr,

respectively.

These estimated reductions were compared with PM2.5 (atmo­

spheric particulate matter with a diameter < 2.5 μm) and non-methane

hydrocarbon (NMHC) emissions recorded in the TEDS10.0 (Lin et al.,

2019), in which the annual emission rates of the food stall category are

287.27 and 178.63 tons/yr, respectively. The corresponding percentage

reductions are 1.8–3.4% and 41.7–44.3% for particulate and gaseous

aldehydes, respectively. These data demonstrate the large potential

impact of the fume collector on the environmental burden of cooking

fumes.

3.3. Design of the fume collector

As previously noted, the new fume collector applied the impinger

concept for the collection of airborne pollutants. The proposed impinger

device effectively collects both gaseous and particulate pollutants

(Guarieiro et al., 2008; Wei et al., 2010), providing a pathway through

which pollutants are efficiently reduced as they come in contact with the

absorption liquid. Several studies have demonstrated that a carefully

selected absorption liquid can achieve high collection efficiencies. For

example, collection efficiencies of up to 100% have been reported for 2′,

7′-dichlorofluorescinand when collecting reactive oxygen species

(Montesinos et al., 2015) and for Griess-Saltzman reagent when col­

lecting NO2 (Filho et al., 2019).

The use of a sodium hypochlorite/surfactant mixing solution to treat

COFs has been described previously. Cheng and Hsieh (2010) achieved a

74% removal efficiency for non-methane hydrocarbons (NMHCs) using

a sodium hypochlorite solution as scrubbing liquid in a wet scrubber; the

efficiency was increased to 86% when a sodium hypochlorite/surfactant

solution was used. In this case, the use of a surfactant increased the ef­

ficiency of the sodium hypochlorite solution in removing NMHCs. Li

et al. (2018) also describe the hydrocarbon removal mechanism of a

sodium hypochlorite/surfactant solution. Briefly, both NaClO and HClO

(a strong oxidant formed from NaClO) can oxidize hydrocarbons and, in

the presence of a surfactant, the surface tension of NaClO aqueous so­

lution decreases, increasing the hydrocarbon solubility and enhancing

oxidation of hydrocarbons. These studies indicate that a sodium hypo­

chlorite/surfactant solution effectively absorbs hydrocarbons, such as

COFs. Indeed, the novel collector used here reduced aldehyde concen­

trations by 76% and 55% on stalls A and B, respectively, which

demonstrated the effectiveness of this design for controlling COFs.

Activated carbon is mainly used to remove odor from COF emissions

(Yang et al., 2007). Foul-smelling COFs associated with pollutants with

low odor thresholds (e.g., reduced sulfur compounds, aldehydes, and

organic acids; Kabir and Kim 2011) can be removed using activated

carbon adsorbents (Taipei Government 2018). Activated carbon is

usually incorporated with other control devices, such as ESPs and wet

scrubbers, to treat COFs (Yang et al., 2007; Gysel et al., 2018). Such

combination systems often achieve high removal efficiencies. For

example, Gysel et al. (2018) reported that a filtration system, an aerosol

grease-removal system, and an ESP-activated carbon combination sys­

tem achieved percentage reductions in particulate matter (PM) of 25%,

58%, and 86%, respectively. For formaldehyde, the respective per­

centage reductions were 13.5%, 52%, and 73%. These data reveal that

the ESP-activated carbon bed combination showed the highest efficiency

at removing PM and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) from cooking

emissions. Furthermore, Yang et al. (2007) compared PM removal effi­

ciencies of ESPs, combined ESP-activated carbon systems, and wet

scrubbers in 12 restaurants, including 5, 3, and 4 restaurants, reporting

average removal efficiencies of 56.0%, 71.6%, and 43.4%, respectively.

Their comparison demonstrates that combined systems can substantially

reduce PM concentrations in cooking exhaust.

3.4. Maintenance frequency and costs

The frequency of maintenance required for the operation of the

proposed fume collector depended on the sodium hypochlorite con­

sumption rate, which is the active ingredient in the COF treatment so­

lution. Table 6 shows the rate at which each stall consumed the NaClO

solution. The reductions in COF emission factors were 0.3 and 0.32 g/h

for stalls A and B, respectively, and the corresponding reductions in the

hexaldehyde equivalent solution were 0.06 and 0.16 mM/h. Assuming a

reaction of one NaClO molecule to one aldehyde molecule, a NaClO

solution with a concentration of 31.6 mM could treat aldehydes emitted

from stalls A and B for 528 and 198 h, respectively. The corresponding

service lives were 66 and 20 d. However, these service life calculations

only account for the time during which NaClO solution in the first bucket

is consumed. Thus, to improve performance, the maintenance time

needed to ensure consistent performance of the fume collector will

depend on the amount of NaClO consumed in the first bucket. Based on

this, the suggested maintenance frequencies for stalls A and B are 4 and

12 times per year, respectively.

Table 6 shows the fabrication and maintenance costs of the fume

collectors. Stalls A and B had fabrication costs of NT$3500 and NT$2800

and annual maintenance costs of NT$624 and NT$1,008, respectively.

Therefore, total costs are in the range of NT$3800–4200. In comparison,

the total capital and annual maintenance costs for ESPs, wet scrubbers,

and the UV/O3 devices are in the range of NT$40,000–200,000 (Taipei

Government 2018). Thus, despite the high collection efficiencies of

these devices, they are unaffordable for many owners of small com­

mercial kitchens. In comparison, the fume collector design described

here offers both an effective and affordable solution for small com­

mercial kitchens.

Regarding management of waste produced by the fume collector, the

NaClO solution was consumed and became inactive for a period a time

(Lenntech 2020), then it could be discharged into surface water with

adequate

amount

of

dilution.

Disposal

of

the

activated

carbon-impregnated polyester filters would be similar to that of other

household waste, i.e., via the local garbage collection system.

3.5. Effect of the cooking fume extraction system on the fume collector

Two factors related to the fume extraction system affected the effi­

ciency of the fume collector. Firstly, a motor in the cooking fume

extraction system was used to drive the emissions through the fume

collector. This motor must provide sufficient power to overcome the

resistance from the fume collector to maintain the minimum transport

velocity needed to prevent the deposition of particulates. Secondly, the

cooking fume extraction system must provide sufficient velocity to

capture the pollutants. With the new fume collector set-up, stall A had a

1.0 horsepower motor that provided an initial duct velocity of 9–10 m/s

and an end velocity of 2.2 m/s; stall B had a 0.5 horsepower motor with

an initial duct velocity of 11–12 m/s and an end velocity of 5–6 m/s.

These velocities met the 5–10 m/s transport velocity recommended by

the American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists

(ACGIH) for conveying fumes and smoke (ACGIH 2013). Furthermore,

both stalls had sufficient end velocities to subsequently release the

treated COFs. Therefore, for both stalls, the fume extraction systems had

sufficient power to overcome the resistance of the fume collector and

maintain suitable transport velocities.

The capturing velocities of stalls A and B were 0.04–0.34 and

0.26–0.35 m/s, respectively (Supplementary Fig. S1), which are below

or just within 0.25–0.5 m/s recommended range for contaminants

released with no velocity into still air (ACGIH 2013). The

fume-extraction systems on both food stalls did not generate sufficient

velocity to draw all cooking fumes into the hood. Therefore, some

cooking fumes were still dispersed into the workplace, especially at the

monitoring sites near cooking sources, such as at the wok edge and in the

cook working area. This is reflected in the lower removal efficiencies at

the wok edge and in the cook working area (49% and 32% for stall A,

and 20% and 33% for stall B) compared to the fume collector outlet

(76% and 55% for stalls A and B, respectively). Cooking fume extraction

systems are usually installed approximately 0.5–1 m above the stove. At

this distance, the velocity at the wok edge is too low to efficiently draw

COFs into the extraction system. The use of an enclosing hood could,

therefore, mitigate this problem as the cross-draft effect on the enclosing

hood would be smaller than on the exterior hood (Canadian Centre for

Occupational Health and Safety, 2016). Our experimental results sup­

port this recommendation, i.e., the enclosing hood used on stall A ach­

ieved greater removal efficiencies compared to the capturing hood of

stall B.

3.6. Limitations and strengths

The following limitations to the study are noted. Firstly, the effec­

tiveness of the new fume collector depended on the performance of the

fume extraction system. Two important factors related to the overall

performance of the fume extraction system are its power and the type of

hood. As previously stated, the collector must have sufficient power to

overcome the resistance from the fume collector and maintain the

minimum transport velocity needed to prevent the deposition of par­

ticulates. Furthermore, the hood should be enclosed as completely as

possible for the efficient capture of pollutants. If these conditions are not

met, the inferior performance of the fume extraction system may limit

the application of the novel collector. In addition, fume extraction sys­

tems that differ from those used on the stalls examined in this study

could obtain different results. To address this, the fume extraction sys­

tems of other stalls should be inspected in advance and any necessary

modifications made to improve transport and capture velocities. This

might include ensuring adequate enclosure of the cooking surface as

well as a good seal between the fume extractor and fume collector.

Secondly, the efficiency of removing odors was not specifically consid­

ered here, which is a major complaint about COFs. However, aldehyde

concentrations were measured to determine the efficiency of the new

collector and, as most aldehydes have a distinctive odor, their efficient

removal will also achieve reductions in COF odors. Thirdly, the new

fume collectors were only installed on two food stalls, and no discernible

trend in the removal of short-chain aldehydes was observed. This small

sample size precludes a general application of the results to all food

stalls, and further investigation of the mechanism through which the

fume collector reduces aldehydes is still needed. Although previous

studies have demonstrated the high efficiency of the NaClO-surfactant

solution in removing hydrocarbons (Cheng and Hsieh 2010; Li et al.,

2018), no studies have yet evaluated the collection efficiencies of acti­

vated carbon-impregnated filters and the effects of different cooking

methods, e.g., barbecuing versus pan-frying. However, despite the small

sample size, this study demonstrates that the proposed fume collector

considerably reduces aldehyde emissions.

The strengths of this study can be summarized as follows. Firstly, the

first application of the impinger concept in the use of a NaClO-surfactant

solution for controlling cooking exhaust has been described. By effi­

ciently exposing COFs to the NaClO-surfactant mixture, the proposed

design facilitates the efficient oxidation of COFs by NaClO. Secondly, the

device was fabricated from easily available and inexpensive materials (i.

e., polypropylene buckets, sodium hypochlorite, neutral detergent, and

activated carbon-impregnated polyester filters). For example, the

fabrication and maintenance costs of the proposed device are estimated

to be in the range of NT$3800–4200, giving a cost-effective solution

alongside COF removal efficiency. The device is also easily modifiable so

that the available space and fume extraction systems of individual food

stalls can be accommodated. Overall, the results described in this study

indicate that the proposed collector can address COF-related problems

in small scale commercial kitchens and food stalls.

4. Conclusions

A fume collector was designed to remove COFs through contact with

a NaClO-surfactant mixture. Aldehyde concentrations were measured to

compare the removal efficiencies of existing collectors and the proposed

device. On stall A, the new collector reduced total aldehyde concen­

trations at the exhaust by 76% (from 342.2 to 80.8 μg/m3); on stall B, the

new collector reduced total aldehyde concentrations at the exhaust by

55% (from 622.7 to 283.1 μg/m3). The corresponding percentage re­

ductions in emission rates were 91% (from 749 to 71 g/yr) and 76%

(from 1040–248 g/h) on stalls A and B, respectively. Large reductions in

cooking fumes were also measured at sites near the cooking source. For

hexaldehyde and nonanal, which are aldehydes abundantly found in

cooking fumes, significant reductions were also observed (6–93% and

20–84%, respectively). The results demonstrated the effectiveness of the

proposed fume collector at removing cooking fumes and reducing the

pollution burden. Additional key advantages of the proposed device are

its cost-effectiveness, easy maintenance requirements, and adaptability

to small cooking workplaces worldwide.
